                            <h3>Understanding Food Composting</h3>
                            <p>Composting food waste is a sustainable way to reduce kitchen waste and enrich your garden
                                soil. It involves the biological decomposition of organic material under controlled
                                conditions to create a nutrient-rich compost.</p>

                            <h3>Setting Up Your Compost Bin</h3>
                            <p>Choose a compost bin or pile in a dry, shady spot near a water source. You can use a
                                tumbler, a stationary bin, or simply designate a small area in your garden for
                                composting. For apartments or small spaces, a countertop or under-sink compost bin works
                                well.</p>

                            <h3>What You Can Compost</h3>
                            <p>Start with vegetable and fruit scraps, eggshells, coffee grounds, and tea bags. These
                                items break down quickly and add valuable nutrients to the compost.</p>

                            <h3>Composting Process</h3>
                            <p>Alternate layers of 'greens' (food scraps) with 'browns' (dry leaves, shredded paper) in
                                your bin. This balance helps maintain the necessary moisture and aeration for efficient
                                decomposition.</p>

                            <h3>Maintaining Your Compost</h3>
                            <p>Regularly mix or turn the compost to oxygenate it and speed up the decomposition process.
                                Keep the compost moist, but not too wet, and cover the bin to maintain moisture and
                                warmth, which are essential for composting.</p>

                            <h3>Using Your Compost</h3>
                            <p>Once your compost turns into a dark, crumbly material with an earthy odor, it’s ready to
                                use. You can add it to your garden beds or use it as potting soil to enrich your plants.
                            </p>
