                            <h3>Compostable Food Scraps</h3>
                            <p>Many kitchen scraps are excellent for composting, turning waste into valuable nutrients
                                for your garden soil. Here’s what you can include:</p>
                            <ul>
                                <li><strong>Fruit Scraps</strong>: Apple cores, banana peels, citrus rinds (in
                                    moderation), and other fruit remains.</li>
                                <li><strong>Vegetable Scraps</strong>: Carrot peels, lettuce, other vegetable leftovers,
                                    and peels.</li>
                                <li><strong>Eggshells</strong>: Crushed eggshells add calcium to the compost, but avoid
                                    adding eggs themselves.</li>
                                <li><strong>Coffee Grounds and Tea Leaves</strong>: Used coffee grounds and tea leaves,
                                    including paper filters and tea bags (if plastic-free).</li>
                                <li><strong>Grains</strong>: Stale bread, cooked rice, pasta, and other grains.</li>
                            </ul>

                            <h3>Foods to Avoid in Compost</h3>
                            <p>While many food scraps benefit your compost, some should be avoided as they can attract
                                pests, create bad odors, or introduce pathogens:</p>
                            <ul>
                                <li><strong>Meat and Fish Scraps</strong>: These can attract rodents and cause
                                    unpleasant odors.</li>
                                <li><strong>Dairy Products</strong>: Cheese, butter, yogurt, and milk products are also
                                    likely to attract pests.</li>
                                <li><strong>Fats and Oils</strong>: These materials can disrupt the composting process
                                    and attract pests.</li>
                                <li><strong>Processed Foods</strong>: Avoid composting heavily processed foods as they
                                    may contain preservatives and other chemicals.</li>
                            </ul>

                            <h3>Best Practices for Composting Food Waste</h3>
                            <p>To maintain a healthy compost, balance your food scraps with 'browns' like dry leaves,
                                straw, or shredded paper. This helps to create the right environment for composting and
                                prevents issues like odor and pests.</p>

