                            <h3>Optimal Preparation of Food Waste</h3>
                            <p>Proper preparation of food waste can significantly enhance the efficiency of the
                                composting process. Here are some tips to prepare your kitchen scraps:</p>

                            <h3>Size Matters</h3>
                            <p>Chop or break down larger food scraps into smaller pieces. Smaller pieces provide more
                                surface area for microorganisms to work on, speeding up the composting process.</p>

                            <h3>Managing Moisture</h3>
                            <p>Food scraps, especially fruits and vegetables, can be high in moisture. Balance this by
                                adding dry materials like leaves, straw, or shredded paper to absorb excess moisture and
                                maintain aeration.</p>

                            <h3>Avoiding Odors</h3>
                            <p>To prevent odors, bury food scraps under a layer of browns or garden soil in your compost
                                bin. This helps in quicker decomposition and minimizes smell.</p>

                            <h3>Composting Citrus and Onions</h3>
                            <p>While citrus peels and onions are compostable, they should be added in moderation. These
                                materials can be acidic and potentially harmful to worms in worm composting systems.</p>

                            <h3>Eggshells</h3>
                            <p>Crush eggshells before adding them to your compost. They are a great source of calcium
                                but take a long time to decompose if left in larger pieces.</p>

                            <h3>Coffee Grounds and Tea Leaves</h3>
                            <p>Used coffee grounds and tea leaves can be added directly to your compost. Ensure to
                                remove any plastic from tea bags, as plastic does not decompose.</p>
